data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort` forcibly kills a thread after a deadline. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006).

## Key Problems in the Original Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()`** — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()`** — same, obsolete and unsupported
3. **`ThreadAbortException`** — never thrown in modern .NET

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` abandons the *wait*, but the work delegate keeps running in the background unless it checks `CancellationToken`. CPU-bound work without checkpoints cannot be truly stopped. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It allocates a timer internally — always `using` it or leaking occurs. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Use the `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If `work` calls a blocking API you can't modify (e.g., native call), the only real kill switch is `Process.Kill` on a child process. No in-process mechanism replaces `Thread.Abort`. |

## Making Work Cooperatively Cancellable

For the timeout to actually stop work (not just abandon the wait), pass the token into the delegate:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

This requires changing the signature to `Func<CancellationToken, T>`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

This is the **recommended** overload — it gives the work a way to cooperate with cancellation.
